      "group": "CLI",
      "groupSlug": "cli",
      "title": "dev",
      "slug": "cli-dev",
      "index": 3,
      "summary": "dev is a Tsundere CLI command. Compile, run, watch, and restart a .yuri project during local development. The command is designed for normal project folders, CI jobs, and local development terminals.",
      "body": "dev is a Tsundere CLI command. Compile, run, watch, and restart a .yuri project during local development. The command is designed for normal project folders, CI jobs, and local development terminals. Start it from the project root after `.env` and `tsundere.config.json` are ready. It watches source files and restarts the runtime build when they change. This matters because Tsundere is meant to feel like a normal developer runtime: commands should work in any project folder, produce readable output, and leave source code separate from generated runtime files. Command architecture: input is read from the current working directory, configuration is resolved from `tsundere.config.json`, package/runtime state is kept in normal project files plus `.tsundere`, and output is designed to be scriptable. Syntax: `tsundere dev`. tsundere dev # edit src/main.yuri # the runtime rebuilds and restarts tsundere dev # edit src/main.yuri # the runtime rebuilds and restarts # Production check tsundere build && npm test Syntax: `tsundere dev`. Common flags: --no-sync, --warnings=false, --verbose. Typical workflow: Start it from the project root after `.env` and `tsundere.config.json` are ready. It watches source files and restarts the runtime build when they change. Related files include `package.json`, `tsundere.config.json`, `tsundere-lock.yaml`, `tsundere-workspace.yaml`, `.tsundere/runtime-build`, and `build` depending on the command. Run `tsundere dev` from the project root unless the command says otherwise. Keep generated output out of source edits. Use command output in CI so failures are visible in logs. Pair CLI changes with `tsundere doctor`, build, and tests before release. Running the command from the wrong folder. Ignoring a failed install or build before starting the runtime. Confusing `tsundere update ` with `tsundere updater` for toolchain updates. Skipping the command-specific troubleshooting note: If the process does not restart, confirm the source directory in `tsundere.config.json` points at the folder you are editing. If the process does not restart, confirm the source directory in `tsundere.config.json` points at the folder you are editing. Run `tsundere doctor` for environment and runtime checks. Run with verbose diagnostics when command output is too short. Check project config, package metadata, and generated runtime directories."
