      "summary": "build is a Tsundere CLI command. Compile .yuri source into runnable JavaScript or TypeScript output and prepare runtime artifacts. The command is designed for normal project folders, CI jobs, and local development terminals.",
      "body": "build is a Tsundere CLI command. Compile .yuri source into runnable JavaScript or TypeScript output and prepare runtime artifacts. The command is designed for normal project folders, CI jobs, and local development terminals. Run before deployment, CI checks, or `tsundere start`. Treat diagnostics as build feedback, not runtime noise. This matters because Tsundere is meant to feel like a normal developer runtime: commands should work in any project folder, produce readable output, and leave source code separate from generated runtime files. Command architecture: input is read from the current working directory, configuration is resolved from `tsundere.config.json`, package/runtime state is kept in normal project files plus `.tsundere`, and output is designed to be scriptable. Syntax: `tsundere build [--protect &lt;profile&gt;]`. tsundere build ls build ls .tsundere/runtime-build tsundere build ls build ls .tsundere/runtime-build # Production check tsundere build && npm test Syntax: `tsundere build [--protect &lt;profile&gt;]`. Common flags: --protect standard, --protect advanced, --source-maps=false. Typical workflow: Run before deployment, CI checks, or `tsundere start`. Treat diagnostics as build feedback, not runtime noise. Related files include `package.json`, `tsundere.config.json`, `tsundere-lock.yaml`, `tsundere-workspace.yaml`, `.tsundere/runtime-build`, and `build` depending on the command. Run `tsundere build` from the project root unless the command says otherwise. Keep generated output out of source edits. Use command output in CI so failures are visible in logs. Pair CLI changes with `tsundere doctor`, build, and tests before release. Running the command from the wrong folder. Ignoring a failed install or build before starting the runtime. Confusing `tsundere update ` with `tsundere updater` for toolchain updates. Skipping the command-specific troubleshooting note: If imports fail after build, run `tsundere runtime install` and `tsundere install` so the local @tsundere/discord package exists. If imports fail after build, run `tsundere runtime install` and `tsundere install` so the local @tsundere/discord package exists. Run `tsundere doctor` for environment and runtime checks. Run with verbose diagnostics when command output is too short. Check project config, package metadata, and generated runtime directories."
