      "summary": "start is a Tsundere CLI command. Run the latest compiled runtime output through the Tsundere runtime entrypoint. The command is designed for normal project folders, CI jobs, and local development terminals.",
      "body": "start is a Tsundere CLI command. Run the latest compiled runtime output through the Tsundere runtime entrypoint. The command is designed for normal project folders, CI jobs, and local development terminals. Use it after `tsundere build` in production or smoke tests so users do not manually call `node build/main.ts`. This matters because Tsundere is meant to feel like a normal developer runtime: commands should work in any project folder, produce readable output, and leave source code separate from generated runtime files. Command architecture: input is read from the current working directory, configuration is resolved from `tsundere.config.json`, package/runtime state is kept in normal project files plus `.tsundere`, and output is designed to be scriptable. Syntax: `tsundere start`. tsundere build tsundere start tsundere build tsundere start # Production check tsundere doctor && tsundere start Syntax: `tsundere start`. Common flags: --env &lt;file&gt;, --check-updates=false. Typical workflow: Use it after `tsundere build` in production or smoke tests so users do not manually call `node build/main.ts`. Related files include `package.json`, `tsundere.config.json`, `tsundere-lock.yaml`, `tsundere-workspace.yaml`, `.tsundere/runtime-build`, and `build` depending on the command. Run `tsundere start` from the project root unless the command says otherwise. Keep generated output out of source edits. Use command output in CI so failures are visible in logs. Pair CLI changes with `tsundere doctor`, build, and tests before release. Running the command from the wrong folder. Ignoring a failed install or build before starting the runtime. Confusing `tsundere update ` with `tsundere updater` for toolchain updates. Skipping the command-specific troubleshooting note: If startup says the runtime build is missing, run `tsundere build` first. If startup says the runtime build is missing, run `tsundere build` first. Run `tsundere doctor` for environment and runtime checks. Run with verbose diagnostics when command output is too short. Check project config, package metadata, and generated runtime directories."
