      "summary": "Empty Project is a practical starter example based on the `empty` style. It explains the project shape, how to run it, and what to change before using it in production.",
      "body": "Empty Project is a practical starter example based on the `empty` style. It explains the project shape, how to run it, and what to change before using it in production. Use this example as a starting point, not as a locked-in framework. Copy the structure, replace placeholders, and keep project-specific behavior inside your own services. Example architecture: src/main.yuri, tsundere.config.json, package.json. Start from the template, keep `main.yuri` focused on startup, and move reusable logic into services so the example can grow without becoming tangled. tsundere create scratch --template empty cd scratch tsundere dev Add one service at a time and keep generated output out of source control. Reference layout: src/main.yuri, tsundere.config.json, package.json. Template: `empty`. Production notes should cover secrets, command sync scope, generated runtime folders, and where project-specific services belong. Treat examples as starting points, not production policy. Replace placeholder IDs, tokens, channels, and guild settings immediately. Move real business logic into services so handlers stay readable. Add tests before turning an example into a deployed bot. Leaving example command names, guild IDs, or channel IDs unchanged. Copying example structure but skipping `.env.example` updates. Turning examples into a hidden framework with too much shared state. Deploying an example before checking permissions and command sync scope. Run the example exactly once before customizing it. Check `.env.example` and replace placeholders with real local values. Use `tsundere build` before `tsundere dev` if syntax errors are unclear. When Discord commands do not appear, confirm guild sync settings and restart the bot."
